<p>Image that we’re testing a class from your project that looks like this:</p>

<dl class="file">
	<dt>src/Math.php</dt>
	<dd><code>&lt;?php

namespace Example;

use RangeException;

class Math
{
    public function add($m, $n)
    {
        return $m + $n;
    }

    public function divide($m, $n)
    {
        if ($n === 0) {
            throw new RangeException();
        }

        return $m / $n;
    }
}</code></dd>
</dl>

<p>Let’s write the unit tests:</p>

<dl class="file">
	<dt>lens/tests/Math.php</dt>
	<dd><code>&lt;?php

namespace Example;

use RangeException;


// Test
$math = new Math();
$c = $math-&gt;add(1, 1);

// Output
$c = 2;


// Test
$math = new Math();
$c = $math-&gt;divide($a, $b);

// Input
$a = 1;
$b = 2;

// Output
$c = 0.5;

// Input
$a = 1;
$b = 0;

// Output
throw new RangeException();</code></dd>
</dl>


<p>Run Lens to see the results:</p>

<code class="terminal">lens Math.php
# Passed tests: 1</code>

<p>Congratulations!
You can test object-oriented code!</p>

<p>Now let’s see what happens when we need a <:link "mock" "get-started/write-a-test/mocks":>.</p>
